00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:55.890
It is fitting that today's
conference on native peoples

00:13:55.890 --> 00:13:59.370
and politics has gathered
so many different people

00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:01.810
in conversation
with one another,

00:14:01.810 --> 00:14:05.300
because the practice
of politics inevitably

00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:07.820
brings vastly
different individuals

00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:10.370
and groups with
multiple priorities

00:14:10.370 --> 00:14:14.110
and conflicting agendas
into common conversation,

00:14:14.110 --> 00:14:16.430
and sometimes combat.

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:20.110
Given where we are in this
year's election cycle,

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:23.350
it can seem like
politics consists solely

00:14:23.350 --> 00:14:27.400
of delegate counts and
convention countdowns.

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:29.820
But if we reduce
politics to nothing

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:33.750
more than election
hoopla, we oversimplify

00:14:33.750 --> 00:14:35.890
what it really means.

00:14:35.890 --> 00:14:39.400
In fact, the equation
of politics with voting

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:42.080
is a fairly recent phenomenon.

00:14:42.080 --> 00:14:45.040
For much of human
existence, voting

00:14:45.040 --> 00:14:48.660
as we understand it today
in our democratic society

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:50.340
has not existed.

00:14:50.340 --> 00:14:53.580
Even when it has,
participation has usually

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:57.410
been restricted to a very
small minority of the world's

00:14:57.410 --> 00:14:59.740
total population.

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:03.850
In reality, the definition of
politics changes over time,

00:15:03.850 --> 00:15:07.830
and it is shaped in unique
ways by different societies

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:09.640
and different cultures.

00:15:09.640 --> 00:15:13.210
People have acted
politically across the globe

00:15:13.210 --> 00:15:15.610
and throughout human
history, but they

00:15:15.610 --> 00:15:20.580
have done so in many other
ways than casting ballots.

00:15:20.580 --> 00:15:24.220
I'm an historian of the
20th century United States.

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:27.220
In the time and
place that I study,

00:15:27.220 --> 00:15:31.500
universal suffrage was
officially the law of the land.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:33.830
But in my research
over the years,

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:37.670
I have found that voting
was not the only or even

00:15:37.670 --> 00:15:42.360
the most common way that
Americans acted politically.

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:46.240
Let me remind you of just
a handful of other ways

00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:49.650
that ordinary people
advocated for their rights

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:53.690
and for the kind of just
society that they desired.

00:15:53.690 --> 00:15:56.440
In the 1930s, working
class Americans

00:15:56.440 --> 00:15:59.370
organized into
industrial labor unions

00:15:59.370 --> 00:16:03.650
to demand a larger share of the
wealth their labor had helped

00:16:03.650 --> 00:16:06.900
to create, to influence
their working conditions,

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:10.770
and to exert more control
over how they allocated time

00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:12.560
in their own lives.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:15.640
From the 1940s
through the 1960s,

00:16:15.640 --> 00:16:19.350
household members and
homemakers took to the streets

00:16:19.350 --> 00:16:22.040
to assert their
power as consumers,

00:16:22.040 --> 00:16:24.820
participating in
boycotts and petitioning

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:27.390
against high
prices, and lobbying

00:16:27.390 --> 00:16:31.300
for greater protections
against unsafe and exploitative

00:16:31.300 --> 00:16:32.690
products.

00:16:32.690 --> 00:16:36.720
In the 1950s and 1960s,
African Americans

00:16:36.720 --> 00:16:39.920
mobilized with strategies
ranging from restaurants

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:43.480
sit-ins to protest marches
to demand their equal rights

00:16:43.480 --> 00:16:46.570
as citizens, creating a
civil rights movement that

00:16:46.570 --> 00:16:50.950
would inspire similar claims by
the American Indian movement,

00:16:50.950 --> 00:16:54.030
feminists, and gay
rights activists.

00:16:54.030 --> 00:16:57.160
Beginning in the 1970s,
political activists

00:16:57.160 --> 00:16:59.860
on the conservative
right from anti-taxers

00:16:59.860 --> 00:17:03.950
to anti-abortion demonstrators,
undertook similar actions

00:17:03.950 --> 00:17:06.339
to promote their causes.

00:17:06.339 --> 00:17:09.740
In all of these cases
and more, Americans

00:17:09.740 --> 00:17:11.890
were acting politically.

00:17:11.890 --> 00:17:15.980
In sum, today's conference is
part of a broader conception

00:17:15.980 --> 00:17:19.200
of political participation
that goes beyond what

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:21.859
happens in the voting booth.

00:17:21.859 --> 00:17:24.369
As we dig deeply into
the multiple ways

00:17:24.369 --> 00:17:26.550
that Native Americans
have registered

00:17:26.550 --> 00:17:29.160
their political
will, we will also

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:32.580
be probing the very
wide range of voices

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:36.120
speaking within those
native communities.

00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:40.800
We will surely see that there
is not one conversation nor one

00:17:40.800 --> 00:17:42.940
uniform point of view.

00:17:42.940 --> 00:17:45.870
I personally look forward to
a day of learning and gaining

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:48.230
new insight and inspiration.

00:17:48.230 --> 00:17:51.890
So let me tell you a little
bit about how today will work.

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:53.930
This morning we
