00:19:34.670 --> 00:19:37.820
the Wampanoag Nipmuc
Massachusetts peoples on whose

00:19:37.820 --> 00:19:39.080
lands we gather today.

00:19:42.210 --> 00:19:46.040
Today's conference is both a
culmination and a beginning.

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:48.310
Let me start with
the culmination part,

00:19:48.310 --> 00:19:50.680
keeping in mind
tomorrow's HUNAP pow wow

00:19:50.680 --> 00:19:54.900
will continue this
important celebration.

00:19:54.900 --> 00:19:57.260
Three years ago
Radcliffe began thinking

00:19:57.260 --> 00:19:59.470
about appropriate themes
for the set of events

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:01.400
that would occur over
a one to one and 1/2

00:20:01.400 --> 00:20:06.300
year period that coincides
with today's conference.

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:10.040
And Radcliffe has embarked upon
this series of conversations

00:20:10.040 --> 00:20:12.310
and events, the
indigenous peoples theme,

00:20:12.310 --> 00:20:15.180
not because the Institute
has a particular expertise

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:19.570
in this area, but because
Radcliffe, and Harvard more

00:20:19.570 --> 00:20:23.960
generally, have clear needs
and obligations to enrich

00:20:23.960 --> 00:20:26.980
our dialogue on native issues.

00:20:26.980 --> 00:20:30.310
A university is a
conversation of a sort,

00:20:30.310 --> 00:20:32.550
a highly bureaucratized
conversation,

00:20:32.550 --> 00:20:36.860
to be sure, but a vital
dialogue nonetheless.

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:39.600
And it is vital to
the future of Harvard,

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:42.830
and in deep consistency
with Harvard's native past,

00:20:42.830 --> 00:20:46.240
that the voice of Native
American and indigenous peoples

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:49.120
be amplified and strengthened.

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:52.680
And it is with thanks to HUNAP
and associated Native Studies

00:20:52.680 --> 00:20:55.720
leaders at Harvard at this
process has been renewing.

00:20:55.720 --> 00:20:58.700
And we at Radcliffe are
pleased and honored to play

00:20:58.700 --> 00:21:01.980
a collaborative part in
this larger and much longer

00:21:01.980 --> 00:21:04.010
term dialogue.

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:09.080
We started in the fall of 2014
with Anishinabe poet Gerald

00:21:09.080 --> 00:21:11.580
Vizenor, who gave
a poetry reading

00:21:11.580 --> 00:21:14.400
and gave thoughtful remarks
on the meaning and intention

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:18.230
of his concept of survivance.

00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:22.190
Professor Angela Riley of
UCLA and a Chief Justice

00:21:22.190 --> 00:21:24.170
of the Supreme Court of
the Citizen Potawatomi

00:21:24.170 --> 00:21:26.890
Nation of Oklahoma,
visited Harvard Law School

00:21:26.890 --> 00:21:30.320
to give a lecture on
indigeneity and law.

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:36.150
Professor Ned Blackhawk of
Yale came in November, 2014

00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:37.970
and gave reflections
on the Sand Creek

00:21:37.970 --> 00:21:42.350
Massacre and its many cultural
and historical legacies.

00:21:42.350 --> 00:21:44.740
This academic year we've
been privileged to be joined

00:21:44.740 --> 00:21:48.010
by two Native American
Radcliffe Fellows, Kristiana

00:21:48.010 --> 00:21:49.816
Kahakauwila, and Alyssa Mt.

00:21:49.816 --> 00:21:51.380
Pleasant.

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:54.410
Professor Kahakauwila just
this Wednesday afternoon

00:21:54.410 --> 00:21:58.304
gave a wonderful reading from
her novel To Weave with Water.

00:21:58.304 --> 00:21:58.845
Professor Mt.

00:21:58.845 --> 00:22:01.303
Pleasant has been working on
her study of the Buffalo Creek

00:22:01.303 --> 00:22:05.200
reservation and gave an
inspiring lecture in the fall.

00:22:05.200 --> 00:22:08.280
Alyssa and Tiana
have both honored

00:22:08.280 --> 00:22:11.020
and enriched us with their
daily presence, their meetings

00:22:11.020 --> 00:22:13.430
with students,
staff, and faculty,

00:22:13.430 --> 00:22:16.080
and other Radcliffe Fellows.

00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:18.100
A third fellow, Carol
Armitage, has also

00:22:18.100 --> 00:22:20.010
been exploring themes
and indigeneity

00:22:20.010 --> 00:22:22.660
in her choreographic work,
and we thank all of them

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:24.710
for their citizenship.

00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:28.070
In January we held a workshop
on the university and indigenous

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:31.280
dispossession, where we learned
what other universities have

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:33.320
been doing to confront
their own relationship

00:22:33.320 --> 00:22:36.640
to indigenous peoples, and
we learned of rich models

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:39.090
for Harvard to emulate.

00:22:39.090 --> 00:22:41.810
And I'm proud to announce
that the Radcliffe Institute,

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:44.650
in collaboration with HUNAP,
the Harvard University Native

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:47.775
American Program, and the
Yale Indian Papers Project,

00:22:47.775 --> 00:22:49.400
and supported by the
Mashpee Wampanoag,

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:53.550
the Nipmuc, the Wampanoag
tribe of Gay Head Aquinna,

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:57.150
and the Mohegan Tribe,
has received a $275,000

00:22:57.150 --> 00:22:59.830
grant from the Council on
Library and Information

00:22:59.830 --> 00:23:04.040
Resources, CLIR, to digitize
more than 4,000 petitions by

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:07.855
and concerning Native Americans
in the Massachusetts archives

00:23:07.855 --> 00:23:09.620
of the Commonwealth.

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:12.225
Collaborative meetings
with tribes for this work

00:23:12.225 --> 00:23:16.050
are underway this spring, and
digitization will begin soon.

00:23:16.050 --> 00:23:18.580
And of course, just
last night Matika Wilbur

00:23:18.580 --> 00:23:20.160
offered a beautiful
presentation,

00:23:20.160 --> 00:23:24.200
opening up her photographic
exhibition, Seeds of Culture:

00:23:24.200 --> 00:23:28.860
The Portraits and Stories
of Native American Women.

00:23:28.860 --> 00:23:30.880
What unites so many
of these events

00:23:30.880 --> 00:23:33.640
forms the theme and title
of today's conference,

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:36.630
Native Peoples, Native Politics.

00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:39.740
In the face of
massive dispossession,

00:23:39.740 --> 00:23:42.920
structural racism, how
have native peoples

00:23:42.920 --> 00:23:46.540
performed what Gerald
Vizenor calls survivance?

00:23:46.540 --> 00:23:50.340
How have they done
political work in doing so?

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:54.490
How have they endeavored to
tell alternative stories?

00:23:54.490 --> 00:23:58.760
How have they drawn upon law,
treaties, and other resources?

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:01.550
How have they formed
alliances and coalitions

00:24:01.550 --> 00:24:04.070
to defend their
sovereignty and dignity

00:24:04.070 --> 00:24:07.080
in the face of
institutionalized erosion,

00:24:07.080 --> 00:24:09.900
in the face of
organized assault?

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:12.110
In talking with Native
American leaders and citizens

00:24:12.110 --> 00:24:15.240
we learn that so much of native
politics and empowerment,

00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:18.040
as Liz Cohen just remarked,
occurs outside the ballot

00:24:18.040 --> 00:24:21.780
box, which is not at all to
say that voting rights are

00:24:21.780 --> 00:24:22.410
unimportant.

00:24:22.410 --> 00:24:24.570
Quite the opposite is
they are under attack

00:24:24.570 --> 00:24:27.450
throughout the land,
including in Indian country.

00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:29.780
But it is to say that
Native Americans have often

00:24:29.780 --> 00:24:32.440
been denied voting rights,
and where they have had them,

00:24:32.440 --> 00:24:35.150
they have often composed
a numerical minority

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:36.950
of the electorate.

00:24:36.950 --> 00:24:40.400
Tools of law, treaty
making and monitoring,

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:43.370
retelling and reframing
stories, building alliances

00:24:43.370 --> 00:24:47.500
and coalitions, resisting,
blogging, protesting, making

00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:50.780
art and politics, and
yes, voting, all of these

00:24:50.780 --> 00:24:55.550
are political and cultural
acts, not just political acts.

00:24:55.550 --> 00:24:58.360
But we should never forget the
deeply political dimensions

00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:00.100
of these acts.

00:25:00.100 --> 00:25:01.980
And what you will hear
today are four panels

00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:05.440
and a keynote address, five
successive conversations,

00:25:05.440 --> 00:25:08.800
if you will, on what
native politics means,

00:25:08.800 --> 00:25:12.490
how it is taking shape, and
how native authors, artists,

00:25:12.490 --> 00:25:15.660
filmmakers, actors,
scholars, and others view

00:25:15.660 --> 00:25:18.860
the political and empowerment
dimensions of their work.

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:24.010
On to beginnings.

00:25:24.010 --> 00:25:25.970
As we look forward
to Harvard's future

00:25:25.970 --> 00:25:29.230
and to Radcliffe's,
it is vital to ensure

00:25:29.230 --> 00:25:32.120
that our discussions
include and incorporate

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:34.610
native and indigenous
perspectives in the themes

00:25:34.610 --> 00:25:37.190
we address, including in
citizenship and urbanism,

00:25:37.190 --> 00:25:39.360
in the years to come,
and that, again, we

00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:42.750
continue to amplify native
presences and native voices

00:25:42.750 --> 00:25:45.270
on Harvard's campus.

00:25:45.270 --> 00:25:48.200
But let me pause with
a sobering statistic.

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:49.980
Just two weeks ago,
Harvard's Office

00:25:49.980 --> 00:25:53.410
for the Vice Provost of Faculty
Development and Diversity

00:25:53.410 --> 00:25:56.680
released its report
entitled Ten-Year Trends

00:25:56.680 --> 00:25:58.700
in Ladder Faculty.

00:25:58.700 --> 00:26:02.610
And in that report, the
office remarks that, quote,

00:26:02.610 --> 00:26:07.120
and I quote, "We still
need to make more progress,

00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:10.840
as we have only 60 ladder
faculty who are black,

00:26:10.840 --> 00:26:14.260
62 latter faculty
who are Latino,

00:26:14.260 --> 00:26:17.930
and none who are
Native American."

00:26:17.930 --> 00:26:19.780
Let me repeat that.

00:26:19.780 --> 00:26:22.420
60 African American
ladder faculty,

00:26:22.420 --> 00:26:26.730
and by ladder I mean tenure
track, 62 Latino ladder

00:26:26.730 --> 00:26:32.310
faculty, zero Native
American ladder faculty.

00:26:32.310 --> 00:26:34.110
And this report comes
in the same year

00:26:34.110 --> 00:26:37.020
that Northwestern, Yale,
and other universities

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:38.950
are moving forward
with plans to hire

00:26:38.950 --> 00:26:42.810
several native faculty
each, as well as faculty

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:45.420
in Native Studies departments,
which of course do not

00:26:45.420 --> 00:26:46.920
exist here.

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:49.870
And it comes at a time when
Harvard's peer Dartmouth, whose

00:26:49.870 --> 00:26:52.340
charter dedicates it,
like Harvard's does,

00:26:52.340 --> 00:26:55.110
to the education of
Native American youth,

00:26:55.110 --> 00:26:57.590
has native faculty in
several different departments

00:26:57.590 --> 00:27:00.360
across this college.

00:27:00.360 --> 00:27:02.020
This report comes
to us in the middle

00:27:02.020 --> 00:27:05.940
of a presidential campaign,
one that Dean Cohen alluded to,

00:27:05.940 --> 00:27:08.170
which, among other things,
has given us two competing

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:11.020
aspirations that you've
heard of recently,

00:27:11.020 --> 00:27:14.740
one of making
America great again,

00:27:14.740 --> 00:27:17.800
and another of making
America whole again.

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:22.260
I'm not going to tip my hand
as to my intended voting

00:27:22.260 --> 00:27:25.010
patterns in the
fall, but I do prefer

00:27:25.010 --> 00:27:26.780
the latter of
those formulations,

00:27:26.780 --> 00:27:29.640
making whole to making great.

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:32.480
And just this last week
another round of reverberations

00:27:32.480 --> 00:27:35.150
of those phrases, making
whole and making great,

00:27:35.150 --> 00:27:39.770
has made me think, what is it
for a university to be great?

00:27:39.770 --> 00:27:43.720
And what is it for a
university to be whole?

00:27:43.720 --> 00:27:46.440
On the latter of those
questions, wholeness,

00:27:46.440 --> 00:27:50.360
I would not presume to know
an answer to what adds up,

00:27:50.360 --> 00:27:53.040
to what things jointly
and together suffice

00:27:53.040 --> 00:27:55.760
to make a university whole.

00:27:55.760 --> 00:27:57.780
But I can say this.

00:27:57.780 --> 00:28:01.550
The richness of the dialogue
we have witnessed this year

00:28:01.550 --> 00:28:05.160
between HUNAP and Radcliffe
in observing the heroic work

00:28:05.160 --> 00:28:08.310
that Dennis Norman,
Shelly Lowe, Jason

00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:11.490
Packineau, and the
whole HUNAP community

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:15.170
and Harvard's native student
community, we can say

00:28:15.170 --> 00:28:19.740
that Harvard can never be whole
without its indigenous peoples,

00:28:19.740 --> 00:28:22.710
that Harvard can never be whole
without its indigenous history

00:28:22.710 --> 00:28:26.190
fully told and explored,
and that Harvard can never

00:28:26.190 --> 00:28:28.750
be whole until its
indigenous family

00:28:28.750 --> 00:28:32.720
is included fully on
its ladder faculty.

00:28:32.720 --> 00:28:42.140
Beyond this, no university
pretending to be great or whole

00:28:42.140 --> 00:28:45.570
can claim to honor diversity
and inclusion while excluding

00:28:45.570 --> 00:28:48.760
native peoples, native
peoples who are represented

00:28:48.760 --> 00:28:52.230
in the very charter whose
accompanying funds saved

00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:57.470
Harvard from insolvency in 1650,
excluding those native people

00:28:57.470 --> 00:28:59.910
from its ladder faculty.

00:28:59.910 --> 00:29:01.980
So before turning
to today's panel,

00:29:01.980 --> 00:29:06.000
and speaking for myself
only, a white man in alliance

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.020
with my native
sisters and brothers,

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:10.700
let me outline a vision,
sketched in a petition,

00:29:10.700 --> 00:29:15.520
if you will, to make Harvard
whole in the coming years,

00:29:15.520 --> 00:29:17.330
that Harvard bring
Native Americans

00:29:17.330 --> 00:29:19.890
to its tenured
faculty, including

00:29:19.890 --> 00:29:22.870
but not limited to scholars of
the indigenous North American

00:29:22.870 --> 00:29:27.610
experience, history, culture,
religion, spirituality,

00:29:27.610 --> 00:29:32.370
society, and politics, and,
by the way, Federal Indian law

00:29:32.370 --> 00:29:35.410
in the United States,
that Harvard draw

00:29:35.410 --> 00:29:38.500
upon its rich intellectual
and material resources

00:29:38.500 --> 00:29:41.230
to examine America's
relationship with indigenous

00:29:41.230 --> 00:29:45.360
peoples and the long
history of dispossession,

00:29:45.360 --> 00:29:49.240
forcible guardianship, removal,
and compulsory evangelization

00:29:49.240 --> 00:29:51.840
in boarding schools,
to say nothing

00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:56.080
of institutionalized violence.

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:58.800
And finally, that Harvard do
for its own indigenous history

00:29:58.800 --> 00:30:01.070
what Northwestern has
done, what Dartmouth

00:30:01.070 --> 00:30:03.970
has done, what Yale and
Brown are now doing,

00:30:03.970 --> 00:30:07.240
or what the University of
British Columbia has done,

00:30:07.240 --> 00:30:10.080
namely that Harvard do for
its own indigenous history

00:30:10.080 --> 00:30:12.420
what Harvard is doing
now, and next year,

00:30:12.420 --> 00:30:14.480
including proudly and
appropriately, here

00:30:14.480 --> 00:30:17.260
at Radcliffe, in its
commemoration of slavery

00:30:17.260 --> 00:30:19.890
and its own relationship
to racial bondage,

00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:21.440
to do three things.

00:30:21.440 --> 00:30:23.510
A, appoint a
committee to examine

00:30:23.510 --> 00:30:27.220
Harvard's own relationship to
Native American dispossession,

00:30:27.220 --> 00:30:31.270
B, to offer seminars and courses
in which students can join

00:30:31.270 --> 00:30:33.660
with faculty in conducting
research on Harvard's

00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:36.480
indigenous history,
painful and even

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:39.920
embarrassing as that
history may be, and C,

00:30:39.920 --> 00:30:42.610
to hold a conference,
as Radcliffe,

00:30:42.610 --> 00:30:44.400
again, will appropriately
and probably

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:47.310
do on slavery in the
university in March

00:30:47.310 --> 00:30:50.475
of 2017, another
conference in the future

00:30:50.475 --> 00:30:54.990
on indigenous dispossession
and the university.

00:30:54.990 --> 00:30:58.050
Making Harvard whole is
something happening today,

00:30:58.050 --> 00:31:03.160
Friday, April 29, in native
peoples doing native politics,

00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:06.510
and in the future by
performing native politics

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:09.500
for and by native peoples.

00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:10.820
Thank you.

00:31:10.820 --> 00:31:21.620
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:21.620 --> 00:31:23.760
So I want to introduce
Maggie McKinley, who's

00:31:23.760 --> 00:31:27.210
the moderator of
our first panel.

00:31:27.210 --> 00:31:30.500
Maggie McKinley is a
Climenko Fellow and Lecturer

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:32.710
of Law at Harvard Law School.

00:31:32.710 --> 00:31:38.150
She's also from the Fond du Lac
Band of Lake Superior Chippewa.

00:31:38.150 --> 00:31:41.630
She writes about legislation,
theories of interpretation,

00:31:41.630 --> 00:31:43.420
minority rights
and representation,

00:31:43.420 --> 00:31:45.800
and federal Indian law.

00:31:45.800 --> 00:31:48.602
And she is the principal
co-investigator

00:31:48.602 --> 00:31:50.810
of the Language of Lobbying
Project at the University

00:31:50.810 --> 00:31:54.730
of Chicago, and
collaborator with me--

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:57.490
and I'm honored to say that--
with the North American

00:31:57.490 --> 00:32:01.870
Petitions Project at the Harvard
Department of Government.

00:32:01.870 --> 00:32:05.380
I rarely describe a paper
and essay as brilliant,

00:32:05.380 --> 00:32:08.640
but I want to alert you
all to her brilliant essay

00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:11.860
coming out in next month's
Stanford Law Review-- it is

00:32:11.860 --> 00:32:12.660
next month, right?

00:32:12.660 --> 00:32:15.500
It hasn't been postponed--
entitled "Lobbying

00:32:15.500 --> 00:32:17.220
and the Petition Clause."

00:32:17.220 --> 00:32:19.660
I've been working on
