00:34:13.719 --> 00:34:17.590
It's been a pleasure to work
with all of you, and an honor.

00:34:17.590 --> 00:34:19.290
I'd like to extend a
very special thanks

00:34:19.290 --> 00:34:22.650
to Dan Carpenter, the
political scientist

00:34:22.650 --> 00:34:25.489
mastermind behind
our thematic year

00:34:25.489 --> 00:34:30.260
of the Performance of Native
Politics Outside the Vote.

00:34:30.260 --> 00:34:33.810
We often envision voting
as the primary mechanism

00:34:33.810 --> 00:34:37.040
of representation
in a democracy.

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:40.159
So why exactly did we
focus our thematic year

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:45.010
on participation
outside of the vote?

00:34:45.010 --> 00:34:50.280
In 1924, Native Americans
were extended the franchise

00:34:50.280 --> 00:34:52.638
in federal elections.

00:34:52.638 --> 00:34:53.429
You heard me right.

00:34:53.429 --> 00:34:55.400
That was 1924.

00:34:55.400 --> 00:34:56.520
19.

00:34:56.520 --> 00:35:00.400
That was 54 years
after the ratification

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:05.690
of the 15th Amendment, which
outlawed extending the right

00:35:05.690 --> 00:35:08.500
to vote on the basis of race.

00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:13.890
And it wasn't until 1964 that
natives were given the right

00:35:13.890 --> 00:35:16.810
to vote in states like Utah.

00:35:16.810 --> 00:35:19.940
In Minnesota, where
my family is from,

00:35:19.940 --> 00:35:22.020
the Minnesota
constitution contained

00:35:22.020 --> 00:35:26.230
an explicit civilization
clause that required natives

00:35:26.230 --> 00:35:30.370
to pass a civilization test
before a district judge

00:35:30.370 --> 00:35:35.550
before being able to vote
in Minnesota elections.

00:35:35.550 --> 00:35:39.060
This means that for a majority
of this nation's history,

00:35:39.060 --> 00:35:44.190
over 150 years, Native
Americans were excluded

00:35:44.190 --> 00:35:46.830
from the primary mechanism
of representation

00:35:46.830 --> 00:35:49.230
in our government.

00:35:49.230 --> 00:35:52.380
Our tribal governments
still have no formal means

00:35:52.380 --> 00:35:56.570
of representation in our
federal and state systems.

00:35:56.570 --> 00:35:59.570
We've had to find ways to
advocate for our sovereignty

00:35:59.570 --> 00:36:02.380
elsewhere.

00:36:02.380 --> 00:36:06.200
Luckily for our communities,
sovereignty is like water,

00:36:06.200 --> 00:36:08.350
and when one channel
is closed, it

00:36:08.350 --> 00:36:12.030
flows into whatever
channels are open to it.

00:36:12.030 --> 00:36:15.090
We'll hear later today about
efforts aimed at Congress

00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:17.710
and the Executive
Branch, and also efforts

00:36:17.710 --> 00:36:23.060
aimed at the public
through art and mass media.

00:36:23.060 --> 00:36:26.570
But we'd like to start
first with the courts.

00:36:26.570 --> 00:36:28.610
This is the site where
the United States first

00:36:28.610 --> 00:36:34.080
articulated the famous words,
domestic dependent nations,

00:36:34.080 --> 00:36:36.640
and in so doing
named what some call

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:39.930
federal recognition
of tribal sovereignty,

00:36:39.930 --> 00:36:41.630
and what others--
not so friendly--

00:36:41.630 --> 00:36:45.570
call a legal fiction.

00:36:45.570 --> 00:36:47.810
In many ways, the
story of native America

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:50.730
within the courts
is a familiar one.

00:36:50.730 --> 00:36:53.240
Like many other
disenfranchised, discrete,

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:56.230
and insular minorities,
natives took to the courts

00:36:56.230 --> 00:36:58.360
during the Civil
Rights era to bring

00:36:58.360 --> 00:37:01.600
the tools of impact litigation
to bear on the problems

00:37:01.600 --> 00:37:05.140
that the electoral branches
just would not solve.

00:37:05.140 --> 00:37:09.090
Like Brown v. Board, Roe v.
Wade, and Romer v. Evans,

00:37:09.090 --> 00:37:13.150
natives saw some
successes in the courts.

00:37:13.150 --> 00:37:16.190
But the native story
is also distinctive.

00:37:16.190 --> 00:37:19.290
Unlike the traditional liberal
integrationist approach

00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:21.540
of other minority
groups, natives

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:24.410
enjoyed structural
protection as minorities

00:37:24.410 --> 00:37:28.630
through sovereignty and
local self-governments,

00:37:28.630 --> 00:37:30.210
and not simply
through the protection

00:37:30.210 --> 00:37:32.890
of constitutional rights.

00:37:32.890 --> 00:37:36.240
Over time the courts have
become increasingly hostile

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:38.690
to the structural protection.

00:37:38.690 --> 00:37:42.440
Not only is it something foreign
to other minority groups,

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:44.350
the court began to
see native sovereignty

00:37:44.350 --> 00:37:47.070
as something that was actually
in tension with the rights

00:37:47.070 --> 00:37:50.370
of others, mostly the
rights of non-Indians

00:37:50.370 --> 00:37:53.340
within Indian country.

00:37:53.340 --> 00:37:55.780
Rather than rights
saving minorities

00:37:55.780 --> 00:37:58.350
from the local
control of federalism,

00:37:58.350 --> 00:38:00.890
as we often hear in our
oversimplified story

00:38:00.890 --> 00:38:04.140
of the Warren Court and
the Civil Rights era,

00:38:04.140 --> 00:38:06.590
we've seen a much more
nuanced relationship

00:38:06.590 --> 00:38:09.560
between natives and the courts.

00:38:09.560 --> 00:38:11.670
It's this more
nuanced relationship

00:38:11.670 --> 00:38:14.590
that our panel explores today.

00:38:14.590 --> 00:38:17.080
And to foster that
discussion, we'll

00:38:17.080 --> 00:38:18.730
begin with someone
that I like to think

00:38:18.730 --> 00:38:22.080
of as the conductor of the
National Symphony of Indian law

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:26.830
litigation, Richard Guest, Staff
Attorney the Native American

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:30.510
Rights Fund and head of its
Tribal Supreme Court Project,

00:38:30.510 --> 00:38:32.825
and in full disclosure,
my former boss.

00:38:35.620 --> 00:38:38.030
If there's a single case
in the entire United

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:42.170
States and elsewhere that's
important to Indian country,

00:38:42.170 --> 00:38:44.290
I have no doubt that
Richard knows about it

00:38:44.290 --> 00:38:48.790
and is organizing everything
around it already.

00:38:48.790 --> 00:38:52.350
And we'll also hear from the
Honorable Diane Humetewa,

00:38:52.350 --> 00:38:55.810
United States District Judge
for the District of Arizona,

00:38:55.810 --> 00:38:59.820
citizen of the Hopi
Nation, and the very first

00:38:59.820 --> 00:39:03.810
Native American woman
appointed to the Federal bench.

00:39:03.810 --> 00:39:07.190
Please join me in
welcoming our panel.

